Definition of Success

In this section, we analyze the characteristics of clients according to their definition of success. Overall, we collect information about the following definitions of personal and business success:

Personal

  1. Business: A successful person is defined by its businessâ success.
  2. Household: A successful person is defined by stability in their household/family.
  3. Community: A successful person is defined by their contribution to the community.

Business

  1. Growth: A successful business is defined by its economic growth.
  2. Stability: A successful business is defined by financial stability and the fact that it can provide to their household.
  3. Community: A successful business is defined by their contribution to the community through positive changes or employment.

The objective is to characterize clients according to their definitions of success, both by comparing characteristics between clients, but also identifying in a data-driven way different clusters of individuals according to their characteristics, especially regarding their beliefs about success.

Personal definition of success

The following tables characterizes the attitudes of the previous groups regarding success at a personal level, in addition to general situation of the business and demographic characteristics. First, we analyze customers that either donât have a business anymore or declare to have never had a business against those that currently own a business. The following plot shows that for those that no longer have a business, their main focus is on their household, while for clients who currently have a business their definition of personal success is tightly linked to that business.

Figure 1. Definition of personal success by whether clients currently have a business or not

In the following analysis we only focus on people who currently have a business. Unsurprisingly, clients that tie personal success to business growth, have both higher initial amounts for loans, as well as business surplus. They also have slightly lower levels of risk aversion and loss aversion, and are willing to invest more in their business. These type of clients are also more ambitious with respect to their business, and have overall higher growth. Finally, they have higher educational levels than their counterparts.

To understand whether there are significant differences between clients that have a business orientation and a non-business orientation, we compare both groups under the same characteristics. Similar patterns arise, showcasing that clients with a business orientation towards personal success also have better performance and higher ambitions for their business. One interesting pattern that emerges is that women are more likely to have a business-oriented definition of success at a higher rate than men.

Identifying optimal clusters

We would also like to know whether the beliefs and/or characteristics of the clients can be grouped in a data-driven way, so we can identify the optimal number of groups or clusters within our data. For this, we conduct a K-means cluster analysis, an unsupervised machine learning method to find the optimal number of clusters based on a set of characteristics. In this case, we provide the models with the attitudes towards success, demographic characteristics, and information about their business, to see whether there are significant differences between definitions of success according to these groups.

Comparing these 4 optimal clusters in terms of definition of success, we note that cluster 1 groups individuals that are more business-oriented, while cluster 2 identifies those that have a stronger family/stability inclination. Cluster 3, in this case, contains clients that have a business-oriented definition of success in the personal arena, but leaning more towards stability in the business sense. Finally, cluster 4 groups individuals similar to cluster 3, but with an overall focus in community, family, and stability over business. For simplicity, we will name the clusters as following, according to their orientation:

  • Cluster 1: Business
  • Cluster 2: Household/stability
  • Cluster 3: Business/stability
  • Cluster 4: Not business
